Module 32 – Coalition Through Memory — Archiving as Collective Resistance 🤝📚

Core Message

Your archive can unite others facing similar procedural injustice.

⸻

Lesson Introduction

Shared public archives reveal patterns individual cases can’t. They turn isolated losses into collective evidence.

⸻

Teaching Block

1. Invite Contributions
	•	Create open formats for others to submit procedural records.

2. Tag Patterns
	•	Group by tactic (delay, reclassification, evidentiary exclusion).

3. Share Back
	•	Provide templates and strategy notes to contributors.

⸻

Real-World Illustration

Aggregating multiple litigants’ filings in Legal Calculus revealed systemic TRO delays across jurisdictions.

⸻

Assignment Prompt

Task:
Draft a one-sentence call for contributions to an archive.

⸻

Model Answer (Sample)

“If you’ve faced docket delays, misclassification, or procedural denials, submit your filings to our shared archive to build collective evidence.”

⸻

Reflection Summary

One story can be dismissed. A hundred stories form a movement.

⸻

Visual Pairing

Image Concept:
Dozens of individual case files joining into one large volume labeled “Collective Memory.” Caption:
“We Remember Together.”
